    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p>A <strong>caption</strong> is the written text that accompanies an image, video, or carousel on a social platform. It supplies context, story, and a call to action — and is the single largest lever creators have on engagement, because platform algorithms reward the comments, saves, and shares that a good caption unlocks. Character limits range from <strong>280 (X) to 4,000 (TikTok)</strong>.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Instagram limit</div>
            <div class="tms-value">2,200 characters</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Social Media</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Engagement lift</div>
            <div class="tms-value">+60% (story-driven)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Beginner</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">The visual stops the scroll. The caption converts the stop into an action — a save, a comment, a share, a click on the link in bio. Weak captions cap even the best creative. Strong captions turn ordinary visuals into distribution.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is a caption?</h2>
        <p>A social caption is the written body that sits beneath (or beside) the visual asset in a post. It performs three jobs at once: gives the visual context, deepens the story, and tells the reader what to do next.</p>
        <p>Every major platform treats caption text differently. Character limits, truncation behaviour, and algorithmic weight vary — which is why the same caption should never be cross-posted without editing.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Caption ≠ closed captions</div>
          <p>Social <strong>captions</strong> are the marketing copy under a post. <strong>Closed captions</strong> are the on-screen subtitles that transcribe spoken audio in videos. Both are essential — Meta reports that closed captions lift video view time <strong>up to 80%</strong> because 85% of Facebook video plays start with sound off. See <a href="/glossary/closed-captions/">closed captions</a>.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why captions matter</h2>
        <p>Every social algorithm rewards engagement, and engagement is a caption problem. Five reasons captions are the highest-leverage social skill:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Comments compound reach.</strong> Comments signal "this content is worth talking about." A single reply-worthy question in the caption can 5-10x reach.</li>
          <li><strong>Saves signal value.</strong> Instagram and TikTok weight saves heavily because they indicate the content is worth returning to. Captions that summarize a takeaway earn saves.</li>
          <li><strong>Shares carry the algorithm to new users.</strong> Shareable captions — controversial takes, contrarian data, useful lists — get pushed out of your follower graph and into recommendations.</li>
          <li><strong>Dwell time is measurable.</strong> Long, well-structured captions that people actually read create dwell time signals that outrank shorter posts.</li>
          <li><strong>Caption keywords power search.</strong> Instagram, TikTok, and LinkedIn search now index caption text. A well-worded caption is basically <a href="/glossary/tiktok-seo/">TikTok SEO</a>.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How a great caption works — the 3-part structure</h2>
        <p>Every high-performing caption follows the same skeleton: <strong>hook, body, close</strong>.</p>

        <h3>Hook (line 1 — before the "more" fold)</h3>
        <p>Captions truncate at ~125 characters on Instagram and ~140 on LinkedIn. The first line has to earn the tap. Proven hook patterns:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Contrarian claim</strong> — "The 6-figure launch that started with 400 followers."</li>
          <li><strong>Bold number</strong> — "$50K client turned down. Here's why."</li>
          <li><strong>Curiosity gap</strong> — "The 3 emails that saved my agency in 2024."</li>
          <li><strong>Direct question</strong> — "Would you fire a $10K/mo client to protect a team member?"</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Body — deliver the promise</h3>
        <p>Short sentences. Line breaks after every 1-2 lines. No corporate blocks of text. Deliver the value the hook promised — a story, a list, a data drop, a lesson.</p>

        <h3>Close — the call to action</h3>
        <p>Every caption needs a job for the reader. Explicit CTAs beat vague ones:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><em>"Save this if you're rebuilding your ICP."</em></li>
          <li><em>"Tag someone this reminded you of."</em></li>
          <li><em>"Full breakdown in the link in bio."</em></li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="types">Caption length by platform</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Platform</th><th>Character limit</th><th>Sweet spot</th><th>Hashtag rules</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="row-highlight"><td><strong>Instagram</strong></td><td>2,200</td><td>150-2,000</td><td>3-5 in caption is optimal</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>LinkedIn</strong></td><td>3,000</td><td>1,300-1,900 for storytelling</td><td>3 branded/topic hashtags</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>TikTok</strong></td><td>4,000 (expanded 2024)</td><td>150-300 for reach; longer for search</td><td>3-5 mixed broad + niche</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>X (Twitter)</strong></td><td>280 (25,000 for Premium)</td><td>Under 240</td><td>1-2 max; often hurt reach</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Facebook</strong></td><td>63,206</td><td>Under 80 for reach</td><td>Minimal impact</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>YouTube Shorts</strong></td><td>100 (title) + 5,000 (description)</td><td>Title under 60</td><td>3-5 hashtags in title</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real caption examples that worked</h2>

        <h3>1. Contrarian LinkedIn opener</h3>
        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># Opening line only — hooked 400+ comments</span><br>
          <span class="uf-new">"I turned down a $50K client last month."</span><br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># Curiosity gap forces the "see more" tap.</span>
        </div>
        <p>Body explained the values misalignment. CTA asked "Have you ever fired a client?" — the question generated 400+ replies and pushed reach past 80K impressions.</p>

        <h3>2. Data-anchor Instagram carousel</h3>
        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-new">"Save rate on this Reel: 5.2%. Here's the caption formula."</span><br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># Specific number + promise of formula = save trigger.</span>
        </div>

        <h3>3. Storytelling short-form video</h3>
        <p>Fitness brand paired a 15-second workout Reel with a 900-character caption breaking down the technique step by step. Save rate: 5.2%. That save rate signaled "worth returning to" and the algorithm pushed the video from 12K to 480K plays inside 72 hours.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Caption vs headline vs subject line — same job, different rules</h2>
        <p>Captions, headlines, and email subject lines all compete for one thing: the first micro-attention grab. But the constraints differ.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Social caption</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Visible after the visual hooks the scroll</li>
              <li>150-3,000 chars depending on platform</li>
              <li>Can build a full story or list</li>
              <li>Engagement = comments, saves, shares</li>
              <li>Optimized for algorithm + reader</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Headline / <a href="/glossary/subject-line/">subject line</a></h4>
            <ul>
              <li>The primary hook — no visual carrying weight</li>
              <li>40-90 chars typical</li>
              <li>Single-sentence promise</li>
              <li>Engagement = clicks or opens</li>
              <li>Optimized for the click, not the read</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 caption best practices</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Front-load the hook.</strong> Never bury the strongest sentence — put it before the "more" fold.</li>
          <li><strong>Write for one reader.</strong> "You" outperforms "you all." Address the person, not the audience.</li>
          <li><strong>Use line breaks aggressively.</strong> Single-line paragraphs. White space is the reading aid on mobile.</li>
          <li><strong>Match voice to platform.</strong> LinkedIn tolerates polished; TikTok rewards raw. Reuse the story, not the register.</li>
          <li><strong>End with a specific ask.</strong> "Comment 'template' and I'll DM it" beats "let me know your thoughts."</li>
          <li><strong>Test hook lengths.</strong> The same story with a 6-word opener vs a 20-word opener can swing reach 3-5x. A/B test hooks weekly.</li>
          <li><strong>Add closed captions to every video.</strong> The 85% of viewers watching muted need the video captioned to stay watching.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common trap — engagement bait</div>
          <p>Meta and TikTok both penalise <a href="/glossary/engagement-bait/">engagement bait</a> — "Like if you agree, share if you don't." Algorithmic detection catches manipulative phrasing and demotes reach. Ask real questions instead. "What would you have done in this situation?" beats "TAG A FRIEND WHO NEEDS THIS."</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common caption mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Burying the hook</strong> — the strongest line lives in paragraph three where nobody reads.</li>
          <li><strong>Copy-pasting across platforms</strong> — tone, length, and hashtag rules differ. Rewrite every time.</li>
          <li><strong>Vague CTAs</strong> — "Thoughts?" gets 3 comments. "What would you have done?" gets 300.</li>
          <li><strong>Hashtag stuffing</strong> — 30 hashtags looks spammy and no longer helps Instagram reach.</li>
          <li><strong>Skipping the CTA</strong> — a caption with no next step gets a like at best.</li>
          <li><strong>Forgetting closed captions on video</strong> — muted viewers churn immediately without them.</li>
          <li><strong>Sounding like a brand</strong> — voice-matched captions from real humans outperform corporate copy every time.</li>
        </ul>

